{"key":"processedPost-16384197","value":{"id":16384197,"first":16383031,"last":16459484,"when":1339763635,"utime":"06/15/12 03:33 PM","content":"Also, to the original poster, misting once a day isn't enough, especially with 1/4 pint cakes and only 2\" of perlite.&nbsp; Step it up to several misting sessions per day.<br /><br />As Frank said above, fresh air exchange is extremely important, not just for fruit development but also for contamination resistance.&nbsp; There is always going to be mold spores landing on your projects because it's in the air everywhere.&nbsp; The trick is to provide an environment which favors mushroom mycelium and not molds.&nbsp; Molds like still, stale air, and mushroom mycelium likes fresh, moving air.&nbsp; That's why your shotgun terrarium outperformed the manure tray.&nbsp; Step up the fanning out of that tray or get some larger holes in it and mist more to make up for the moisture that is lost due to that extra fresh air.<br /><br />Congrats!&nbsp; I can definitely say those look a lot better than my first attempts at indoor growing.<br />RR","title":"Re: Greetings Shroomerites","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}